      <hedline>
        <hl1>Our Thirst for Oil: It's Time to Cut Back</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Charles Borton letter says it is long past time for US to develop energy policy that concentrates on conservation and renewable energy resources (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your Sept. 13 editorial ''The Latest Oil Shock'' states that ''the best solution'' to controlling high oil prices ''would be a steep increase in production by oil producers, especially Saudi Arabia.'' Philip K. Verleger Jr. (''Taking Power Over Oil,'' Op-Ed, Sept. 13) suggests tapping the strategic oil reserves.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your Sept. 13 editorial ''The Latest Oil Shock'' states that ''the best solution'' to controlling high oil prices ''would be a steep increase in production by oil producers, especially Saudi Arabia.'' Philip K. Verleger Jr. (''Taking Power Over Oil,'' Op-Ed, Sept. 13) suggests tapping the strategic oil reserves.</p>
        <p>These are both short-term solutions.</p>
        <p>It's long past time for our country to develop an energy policy that focuses on conservation, efficiency and, in the long term, renewable energy resources. This could dramatically reduce our dependence on oil.</p>
        <p>Reduced demand may then lower prices, but ideally we will get to the point where our economy doesn't rest on the price of oil.</p>
        <p>CHARLES BORTON  Clinton, N.Y., Sept. 13, 2000</p>
      </block>
